Note:
Thread-local storage (TLS) API for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This module implements a process-wide TLS registry. Callers obtain an opaque
integer KEY from tls_key_create and then associate one Integer value with that
key per thread. The pair (current_thread_id, key) is the lookup identity, so the
same key resolves to a different value on every thread — exactly the thread-local
semantics callers expect.

The registry is a single dynamically-grown table of fixed-size entries protected
by ONE process-wide RuntimeMutex (from the completed runtime mutex layer). The
mutex, the table, and the bookkeeping counters all live in a single state block
that is allocated lazily on first use and cached in a module-level pointer.

State block layout (40 bytes):
    offset 0:  table     — pointer to the entry array (the live registry)
    offset 8:  count     — number of slots currently in use (the high-water mark;
                           includes tombstones so addresses stay stable)
    offset 16: capacity  — number of entry slots the table can hold
    offset 24: next_key  — monotonically increasing key counter (next id to hand out)
    offset 32: mutex     — the RuntimeMutex handle guarding every access

Entry layout (32 bytes):
    offset 0:  thread_id — owning OS thread id (from thread_current_id)
    offset 8:  key       — the key id this entry binds
    offset 16: in_use    — 1 live, 0 free/tombstone
    offset 24: value     — the stored Integer value

The spec for this module documents the first three entry fields at offsets 0, 8,
and 16. Those three offsets are preserved here exactly; the value an entry must
carry is stored immediately after them at offset 24, giving a 32-byte entry. A
24-byte entry physically cannot hold thread_id, key, in_use AND a value, so the
table widens to 32 bytes while keeping every documented offset stable.

Removal is a tombstone (in_use cleared) rather than a compaction so that no entry
address held across a call is invalidated; tombstoned slots are reused by the
next insert before the table grows. The table doubles in capacity when an append
finds it full.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/thread_core.runa" as Thread
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: Status codes returned by the TLS API
Constant TLS_OK as Integer is 0
Constant TLS_ERR as Integer is 0 minus 1

Note: State block layout
Constant TLS_STATE_SIZE as Integer is 40
Constant TLS_STATE_OFF_TABLE as Integer is 0
Constant TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 8
Constant TLS_STATE_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 16
Constant TLS_STATE_OFF_NEXT_KEY as Integer is 24
Constant TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 32

Note: Entry layout
Constant TLS_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD as Integer is 0
Constant TLS_ENTRY_OFF_KEY as Integer is 8
Constant TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE as Integer is 16
Constant TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE as Integer is 24

Note: Initial table capacity in entries; doubled on overflow
Constant TLS_INITIAL_CAPACITY as Integer is 16

Note: Cached pointer to the lazily-allocated registry state block (0 = not yet built)
Let tls_state be 0

Process called "tls_ensure_state" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Every public entry point needs the registry before it can do anything, so the
    registry is built on first touch rather than at module load. Building it here
    keeps the public API free of an explicit init call and lets the very first
    operation (typically tls_key_create at program startup) bring the table and
    its guarding mutex into existence together.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    If the cached state pointer is already set, return it. Otherwise allocate the
    state block, then the initial entry table, then create the registry mutex.
    The table is allocated before the mutex so that a mutex-creation failure has
    nothing leaked to clean up beyond two deallocations. Zero every slot's in_use
    field so freshly allocated slots read as free, seed the counters (count 0,
    capacity TLS_INITIAL_CAPACITY, next_key 1 so the first handed-out key is 1),
    store the mutex handle, publish the state pointer, and return it. Any
    allocation failure unwinds what was acquired and returns 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two allocations plus one mutex_new on the cold path, executed once per process.
    Every later call is a single pointer load and compare.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    First use must happen before the program spawns the threads that will share
    this registry — the standard lifecycle, since keys are created at startup. The
    lazy build is not itself serialized (the guarding mutex does not exist until it
    completes), so two threads racing the very first call could each build a state
    block; the registry is therefore initialized on the main thread before fan-out.
    A failed build returns 0 and every caller treats 0 as out-of-memory.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tls_state is not equal to 0:
        Return tls_state
    End If

    Let st be proc allocate from Memory with TLS_STATE_SIZE
    If st is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let initial_bytes be TLS_INITIAL_CAPACITY multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let tbl be proc allocate from Memory with initial_bytes
    If tbl is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with st
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with tbl
        proc deallocate from Memory with st
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than TLS_INITIAL_CAPACITY:
        Let slot be tbl plus (i multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with st, TLS_STATE_OFF_TABLE, tbl
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with st, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with st, TLS_STATE_OFF_CAPACITY, TLS_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with st, TLS_STATE_OFF_NEXT_KEY, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with st, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX, mtx

    Set tls_state to st
    Return st
End Process

Process called "tls_entry_addr" takes state as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Entry addresses are needed in several places (find, insert, grow, clear). One
    computation point keeps the stride arithmetic correct and consistent and reads
    the table pointer fresh each time so callers stay correct across a grow that
    reallocated the table.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Load the current table base from the state block and add index times the fixed
    entry stride.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load, one multiply, one add. No branches.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Internal helper. The caller is responsible for passing an index within the
    table's current capacity; callers here only ever pass indices in [0, count].
    @End Security_Scope

    Let tbl be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_TABLE
    Return tbl plus (index multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE)
End Process

Process called "tls_find_slot" takes state as Integer, tid as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lookup, presence test, update, and removal all need the same scan for the live
    entry matching a (thread, key) pair, so the scan lives in one place to keep the
    four public operations identical in how they identify an entry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk slots [0, count). Skip tombstones (in_use 0). For a live slot, compare its
    thread_id then its key against the requested pair and return the slot address on
    a full match. Return 0 when no live entry matches.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Linear over the in-use high-water mark. The registry holds one entry per live
    (thread, key) pair, which is small for typical thread-local usage; tombstones
    are reused by inserts so the scan length stays bounded by live demand.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Internal helper, called only with the registry mutex held so the table cannot
    be reallocated underneath the scan.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot be tls_entry_addr(state, i)
        Let in_use be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE
        If in_use is equal to 1:
            Let slot_tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD
            If slot_tid is equal to tid:
                Let slot_key be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_KEY
                If slot_key is equal to key:
                    Return slot
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "tls_grow" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    When an append finds every slot live, capacity must expand so new bindings can
    be stored. Doubling amortizes the copy cost so a run of N inserts stays linear.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a new table of double the capacity. Copy all four fields of every used
    slot [0, count) into the matching slot of the new table so live entries and
    tombstone positions are preserved exactly. Initialize the in_use field of every
    newly added slot to 0 so it reads as free. Free the old table, then publish the
    new table pointer and the new capacity into the state block. Return 1 on success
    and 0 if the new allocation fails (leaving the existing table untouched).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation, a field-wise copy of count entries, and one deallocation. Cold
    relative to ordinary get/set because doubling makes it rare.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Internal helper, called only with the registry mutex held. On allocation
    failure the registry is left fully intact and usable.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let old_cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let new_cap be old_cap multiplied by 2
    Let old_tbl be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_TABLE

    Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let new_tbl be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
    If new_tbl is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let src be old_tbl plus (i multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE)
        Let dst be new_tbl plus (i multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE)
        Let src_tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD
        Let src_key be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_KEY
        Let src_in_use be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE
        Let src_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD, src_tid
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_KEY, src_key
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, src_in_use
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE, src_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    While i is less than new_cap:
        Let slot be new_tbl plus (i multiplied by TLS_ENTRY_SIZE)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Memory with old_tbl
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_TABLE, new_tbl
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_CAPACITY, new_cap
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "tls_key_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Keys must be unique across the whole process so that two unrelated subsystems
    never collide on the same id. A single monotonic counter, advanced under the
    registry lock, guarantees that.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry exists, take the lock, read the next_key counter, store the
    incremented counter back, release the lock, and return the value that was read.
    The first key handed out is 1, so 0 is never a valid key.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip and two field accesses. Called rarely (once per logical
    thread-local slot, at setup), so its cost is irrelevant to the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns TLS_ERR if the registry cannot be built (out of memory). The registry
    mutex is never poisoned by this module, so a successful acquire always returns
    MUTEX_OK (0) with the lock held; any non-zero result means the lock was not
    taken and no counter is advanced.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return TLS_ERR
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return TLS_ERR
    End If

    Let key be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_NEXT_KEY
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_NEXT_KEY, key plus 1
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return key
End Process

Process called "tls_set" takes key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Binding a value for the current thread is an upsert: if this thread already has
    the key, overwrite it in place; otherwise create a new entry. Reusing the
    existing slot keeps a thread's repeated writes from growing the table.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry, take the lock, resolve the current thread id. Look for an
    existing live (tid, key) entry; if found, overwrite its value and return TLS_OK.
    Otherwise find the first tombstone to reuse; if none exists, append at count,
    growing the table first when it is full. Populate the chosen slot's thread_id,
    key, value, and in_use fields, release the lock, and return TLS_OK. A grow
    failure releases the lock and returns TLS_ERR.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip and a single linear scan that doubles as the lookup and the
    free-slot search. Amortized O(1) appends thanks to capacity doubling.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns TLS_ERR on registry build failure, lock-not-taken, or table growth
    failure. The chosen slot address is computed after any grow so it always points
    into the live (possibly reallocated) table.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return TLS_ERR
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return TLS_ERR
    End If

    Let tid be proc thread_current_id from Thread

    Let existing be tls_find_slot(state, tid, key)
    If existing is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with existing, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE, value
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
        Return TLS_OK
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT
    Let found_free be 0
    Let free_idx be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot be tls_entry_addr(state, i)
        Let in_use be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE
        If in_use is equal to 0:
            Set found_free to 1
            Set free_idx to i
            Set i to count
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Let target_index be 0
    If found_free is equal to 1:
        Set target_index to free_idx
    Otherwise:
        Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_CAPACITY
        If count is equal to cap:
            Let grown be tls_grow(state)
            If grown is equal to 0:
                proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
                Return TLS_ERR
            End If
        End If
        Set target_index to count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT, count plus 1
    End If

    Let target be tls_entry_addr(state, target_index)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with target, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD, tid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with target, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_KEY, key
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with target, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with target, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, 1
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return TLS_OK
End Process

Process called "tls_get" takes key as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Read the value this thread bound to the key. Absence is reported as 0 so simple
    callers can treat an unset slot as a zero default without a separate presence
    check; callers that must distinguish "unset" from "set to 0" use tls_has.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry, take the lock, resolve the current thread id, find the live
    (tid, key) entry, and read its value if present. Release the lock and return the
    value, or 0 when there is no matching entry. The lock is held across the read
    because a concurrent tls_set may grow (reallocate and free) the table.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip and one linear scan bounded by the live-entry high-water
    mark.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 if the registry cannot be built or the lock is not taken — the same
    result as a genuine miss, which is the safe default for a value read.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tid be proc thread_current_id from Thread
    Let slot be tls_find_slot(state, tid, key)
    Let result be 0
    If slot is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_VALUE
    End If
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return result
End Process

Process called "tls_has" takes key as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Distinguish "this thread has bound the key" from "value happens to be 0", which
    a bare tls_get cannot express. This is the presence test callers use before
    treating a 0 from tls_get as meaningful.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry, take the lock, resolve the current thread id, and search
    for a live (tid, key) entry. Release the lock and return 1 if one was found, 0
    otherwise.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip and one linear scan; no value read beyond the match test.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 (absent) if the registry cannot be built or the lock is not taken, so
    a caller never falsely believes a binding exists.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tid be proc thread_current_id from Thread
    Let slot be tls_find_slot(state, tid, key)
    Let present be 0
    If slot is not equal to 0:
        Set present to 1
    End If
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return present
End Process

Process called "tls_remove" takes key as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drop this thread's binding for a key while leaving every other thread's binding
    for the same key intact. Removal is idempotent: removing an absent key succeeds.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry, take the lock, resolve the current thread id, and find the
    live (tid, key) entry. If present, clear its in_use flag, turning the slot into
    a tombstone that a later insert can reuse — addresses of other entries stay
    valid because nothing is compacted. Release the lock and return TLS_OK whether
    or not an entry was found. If the registry was never built there is nothing to
    remove, which is also TLS_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip, one linear scan, and a single field store. No allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns TLS_ERR only when the lock cannot be taken. A never-built registry and
    an absent key both return TLS_OK because the post-condition (no such binding) is
    already satisfied.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return TLS_OK
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return TLS_ERR
    End If

    Let tid be proc thread_current_id from Thread
    Let slot be tls_find_slot(state, tid, key)
    If slot is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, 0
    End If
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return TLS_OK
End Process

Process called "tls_clear_current_thread" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A thread about to exit must release every value it bound so its slots are
    reclaimable and stale data never leaks to a future thread that is later assigned
    the same OS thread id. This is the teardown counterpart to tls_set.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ensure the registry, take the lock, resolve the current thread id, and scan all
    used slots. For every live entry whose thread_id matches, clear its in_use flag
    (tombstone it) and count it. Release the lock and return the number of bindings
    removed. A never-built registry removes nothing and returns 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One lock round-trip and a single linear scan over the used slots; one field
    store per removed entry. No allocation or compaction.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Intended to be called exactly once on thread teardown. Returns 0 if the registry
    cannot be built or the lock is not taken (nothing was removed in either case).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be tls_ensure_state()
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_MUTEX
    Let acq be proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    If acq is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tid be proc thread_current_id from Thread
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with state, TLS_STATE_OFF_COUNT
    Let removed be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot be tls_entry_addr(state, i)
        Let in_use be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE
        If in_use is equal to 1:
            Let slot_tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_THREAD
            If slot_tid is equal to tid:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot, TLS_ENTRY_OFF_IN_USE, 0
                Set removed to removed plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return removed
End Process
